Chick weights

The ChickWeight data set is part of the base package datasets. See ?ChickWeight for details on the data. For all of the questions use dplyr functions with the pipe %>% whenever possible.

# library and dataset imports
library(datasets)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
  1. Get a frequency breakdown of the number of chicks, their average weight and the standard deviation of the weights in each of the diets at the start of the study. Store the resulting data frame in a variable named weight0 and print.
# weight0
weight0 <- ChickWeight %>% 
  group_by(Diet) %>%
  summarise(num_chicks = n(),mean_weight = mean(weight, na.rm = TRUE), 
            sd_weight = sd(weight, na.rm = TRUE))

# EXTRA CREDIT: ggplot with error bars
ggplot(data = weight0, aes(x = Diet, y=mean_weight)) + 
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_errorbar(aes(x=Diet, ymin=mean_weight-sd_weight,ymax=mean_weight+sd_weight),
                width=0.2, colour="orange", alpha=0.9, size=1.0) + 
  xlab("Diet Type") +
  ylab("Average Weight") + 
  ggtitle("Average Weight for each Diet with Standard Deviation") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Description: Since I am making calculations on each of the different diets, I started by using the group_by function on the Diet feature. Then, I piped the output of this into the summarise function, where I constructed a new dataframe with the average_weight, sd_weight, and number of chicks for each of these diets. For the extra credit, I constructed a bar plot of Diet vs Average wieght and used “geom_errorbar” to include intervals on each weight.

  1. Each chick should have twelve weight measurements. Use the dplyr package to identify how many measurements are there for each chick. Extract a subset of the data for all chicks with complete information, name the data set complete, and print the first 3 rows. (Hint: you might want to use mutate to introduce a helper variable consisting of the number of observations)
complete <- ChickWeight %>%
  group_by(Chick) %>%
  filter(n() == 12)

  1. In the complete data set introduce a new variable that measures the current weight difference compared to day 0. Name this variable weightgain and print the first 3 rows of the new data frame.

  1. Use {ggplot2} to create side-by-side boxplots of weightgain by Diet for day 21. Change the order of the categories in the Diet variable such that the boxplots are ordered by median weightgain, and the lower limit of the y axis should be 0. Describe the relationship in 2-3 sentences.
complete21 <- complete %>% filter(Time == 21)

complete21 %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x=reorder(Diet, weightgain, FUN=median),
                                      y=weightgain)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + ylim(0, 30) + xlab("Diet") + ylab("Weight Gain") +
  ggtitle("Wight Gain vs Diet For Day 21") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Description: First, I filtered the complete dataset to make a subset of only day 21. Then, I piped the subset into a ggplot where I used the reorder function to sort the weightgain column by mean for each diet.

  1. For the chicks with the least and the most weight at time 0, plot their growth trajectories over time.

The Average Growth Trajectory is the red line for both plots below

time0max <- complete %>% ungroup() %>% filter(Time == 0) %>% filter(weight == max(weight)) 
time0min <- complete %>% ungroup() %>% filter(Time == 0) %>% filter(weight == min(weight)) 

max0Chicks <- complete %>% ungroup() %>% filter(Chick %in% time0max$Chick)
min0Chicks <- complete %>% ungroup() %>% filter(Chick %in% time0min$Chick)

max0Chicks %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Time, y=weight, group=Chick, color=Chick)) + geom_line() + 
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean, aes(group=1), geom = "line", colour="red") +
  ggtitle("Growth Over Time For Chicks With Largest Starting Weight") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

min0Chicks %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Time, y=weight, group=Chick, color=Chick)) + geom_line() + 
  stat_summary(fun.y = mean, aes(group=1), geom = "line", colour="red") +
  ggtitle("Growth Over Time For Chicks With Smallest Starting Weight") + 
    theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Description: First, I filtered the complete dataset to only include rows where the time == 21 and the weight is equal to the max/min. Then, I created a subset of complete which only included Chicks who’s numbers corresponded to the these max/min. Finally, I plotted them.

  1. Add to the previous plot the average growth trajectory for all chicks (calculated as the mean weight for each chick at each time). How do the trajectories compare?

Answer: Looking at both trajectory lines, it appears that chicks who are a smaller weight at day 0 tend to grow larger than those who started out heavier at day zero. The ending average for chicks with a smaller starting weight is around 240 whereas the ending average for chicks that started out larger is not even 200.
